                   predictions confirmed in later behavior. The
                   interpretation of these effects is that prediction of
                   a behavioral sequence evokes a specific cognitive
                   representation of that sequence, which is accessed on
                   subsequent occasions. The results demonstrate the
                   strong effects on behavior of engaging in
                   prebehavioral cognitive work. Relationships to Ajzen
                   and Fishbein's notions of behavioral intentions and
                   Abelson's notion of scripts are spelled out. Since
                   people overpredict desirable behaviors and
