                   low-value reward. A monetary incentive delay task
                   independently localized regions responsive to reward
                   anticipation. In the encoding task, high-reward cues
                   preceding remembered but not forgotten scenes
                   activated the ventral tegmental area, nucleus
                   accumbens, and hippocampus. Across subjects, greater
                   activation in these regions predicted superior memory
                   performance. Within subject, increased correlation
                   between the hippocampus and ventral tegmental area
                   was associated with enhanced long-term memory for the
                   subsequent scene. These findings demonstrate that
                   brain activation preceding stimulus encoding can
                   predict declarative memory formation. The findings
                   are consistent with the hypothesis that reward
                   motivation promotes memory formation via dopamine
                   release in the hippocampus prior to learning.
                   {\textcopyright} 2006 Elsevier Inc. All rights
                   reserved.},
